The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, August 10, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, Aug. 9: Government security prices may stage a rally on Tuesday following the Employees Provident Fund Organisation announcing a reduced interim interest rate of 8.5 per cent for the year. The rate cut was least expected by the bond markets given the coalition nature of the government. The bond markets will be pleasantly surprised. Government security prices may go up early tomorrow, said a dealer with a leading private sector bank.																								 Mumbai, Aug. 9: The Reserve Bank today directed primary urban co-operative banks to scrupulously follow the norms in sanctioning of temporary overdraft or cheque purchase facilities. Violations would attract action under the Banking Regulation Act, 1949, it added.																								 Jakarta, Aug. 9: Opec may raise its production quotas to match current output levels in a measure to prevent further rise in oil prices, said president Purnomo Yusgiantoro. This would be discussed at Opecs meeting in Vienna on September 14.																								 Calcutta, Aug. 9: Essar Steel today said it will issue 0.01 per cent preference shares worth Rs 497 crore to group companies, Essar Power and Essar Investment, at Rs 18.																								 Mumbai, Aug. 9: UTV Software Communications has sold its remaining 44 per cent stake in Vijay Television to STAR India for Rs 31 crore.
